00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:35.430
But I was born in
Brooklyn, Bed Stuy.

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:39.110
And those who may go
to Bed Stuy today,

00:03:39.110 --> 00:03:43.830
you have absolutely no idea
what it looked like in the 19--

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:47.390
in the mid-1970s and the 1980s.

00:03:47.390 --> 00:03:49.970
Because then it was a war zone.

00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:53.280
Then there were heaps
of trash burning

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:58.700
and large tenements that
were completely undealt with.

00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:01.170
It is the largest
black community

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:03.990
in the country, black
neighborhood in the country.

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:06.310
It was one of the
poorest outside of--

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:08.760
in the Northeast,
black neighborhoods

00:04:08.760 --> 00:04:14.162
in the country, and I
lived on the corner.

00:04:14.162 --> 00:04:17.649
Now, I don't know-- anyone
who grew up in a hood,

00:04:17.649 --> 00:04:19.920
like in a ghetto,
in an urban ghetto,

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:22.770
knows what the corner is like.

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:26.350
Because that's where
everything goes down.

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:29.160
And I always asked my mom,
why would you move us here?

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:32.800
Why would you-- you were
in the Black Panther Party.

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:38.050
You knew all about the black
liberation and black power.

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:41.680
Why would you move us to a
place where we could die?

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:42.180
You know?

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:44.115
I felt like that was
a legitimate question.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:51.620
And she would say to me,
well, I could move you

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:53.140
to a white neighborhood.

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:56.980
I could send you somewhere
where you would fear yourself

00:04:56.980 --> 00:04:58.680
and other people like you.

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:01.320
I could put you
in private school,

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:05.880
and you could grow up with lots
of chances, lots of whatever.

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:08.170
But you wouldn't
have fought for that,

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:09.920
and those chances
wouldn't be chances

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:12.810
that then anyone else
around you, other people,

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:14.970
were able to receive
because of you.

00:05:14.970 --> 00:05:19.080
So we're here in order
to fight for our people.

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:22.330
It's not just about you, and
it's not just about your life.

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:25.140
It's about our lives together.

00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:30.720
And it was a hard lesson
for me, because as a child,

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:32.590
it's like, no, it's about me.

00:05:35.190 --> 00:05:39.780
But she made it very clear from
the gate that it's never just

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:42.690
about me.

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:45.660
Another funny thing that
she always used to do,

00:05:45.660 --> 00:05:49.660
or that I think this story
gives you a good picture

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:52.750
into how I came to be here.

00:05:52.750 --> 00:05:56.556
So it was mentioned
that I was poet.

00:05:56.556 --> 00:05:58.840
So I wrote a chat book.

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:00.840
I got it published by
Kitchen Table Press, which

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:04.070
is the press that Audrey
Lorn, and Barbara Smith,

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:06.460
and folks who were originally
affiliated with it.

00:06:06.460 --> 00:06:11.190
And I was about 13
or 14, and my mom--

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:14.880
it was all my mom's pushing
to make that happen.

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:17.580
She bought all these
copies of the book,

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:20.090
and she's like, yes, now
let's go to Restoration Plaza

00:06:20.090 --> 00:06:21.530
and sell these books.

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:23.030
I'm like, OK.

00:06:23.030 --> 00:06:26.490
So I go to Restoration Plaza,
which is like a little shopping

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:27.500
area in Brooklyn.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.000
Sold all the books.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.410
I make like $1,500.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:31.590
I'm so excited.

00:06:31.590 --> 00:06:32.370
I'm like, yes.

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:35.320
I got money in my pocket, I
didn't even have to sell drugs.

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:37.470
I'm rich-- $1,500.

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:40.320
So I bring the money back,
and she's like, OK, great.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:43.020
And she peels off a $100
bill and gives it to me.

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:44.699
I said, I'm confused.

00:06:44.699 --> 00:06:45.990
WILSON WHITE: Yeah, $1,500 is--

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:48.760
MALKIA CYRIL: I sold $1,500
and did all the work.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:51.380
And she said, you know
when you have a gift, that

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:52.640
means you have to give it.

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:53.815
It doesn't belong to you.

00:06:53.815 --> 00:06:56.190
All of the rest of this money
is going to the local women

00:06:56.190 --> 00:06:57.499
and children's shelter.

00:06:57.499 --> 00:06:58.790
And that's what happened to it.

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:01.810
So that's like how
I was raised, right?

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:04.700
You know, it's not
just about you.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:07.980
It's about your people.

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:11.560
When your body is on the
line, it's for a reason.

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:14.990
And so my mom was a member
of the Black Panther Party.

00:07:14.990 --> 00:07:19.740
She ran their breakfast program
in the New York Chapter.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:22.530
She also was editor for the
"Black Panther Newspaper."

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:25.125
So she taught me really early
on an appreciation for art,

00:07:25.125 --> 00:07:28.540
for culture, for words.

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:29.710
She believed in journalism.

00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:31.350
She was an educator.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:33.950
She ran out of the
wider community college

00:07:33.950 --> 00:07:39.040
in New York all of the
educational programs for folks

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:40.810
in prison in New York.

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:43.640
So that is where I come from.

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:48.150
And so coming into a focus on
media and telecommunications

00:07:48.150 --> 00:07:50.530
technology, [AUDIO OUT].

00:07:50.530 --> 00:07:52.560
WILSON WHITE: Having
that background--

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:54.500
MALKIA CYRIL: Yeah, it
was very easy for me.

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:56.291
WILSON WHITE: We're
saying that background,

00:07:56.291 --> 00:07:58.405
the context from your
upbringing, how that made

00:07:58.405 --> 00:08:01.420
the transition into what
you're doing in terms of media

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:02.609
adjustment was fairly easy.

00:08:02.609 --> 00:08:03.400
MALKIA CYRIL: Yeah.

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:05.260
So let me crystallize that.

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:10.890
So number one, in the '80s,
news coverage was filled with

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:14.060
stereotypes about
superpredators,

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:18.260
black teenage superpredators,
black crack babies,

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:20.300
black welfare moms--

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:22.870
black, black, black criminals.

00:08:22.870 --> 00:08:25.470
And that was about me.

00:08:25.470 --> 00:08:29.550
That was about me and my
friends and my family.

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:34.309
And so as I became an
organizer, my first mandate

00:08:34.309 --> 00:08:37.490
was always to address
this question of me

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:40.760
and how the infrastructure
of meaning--

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:43.669
the news, the
education system, all

00:08:43.669 --> 00:08:45.830
of these pieces
of infrastructure

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:48.250
that produce what we read,
watch, and listen to,

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:50.320
how they're implicated.

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:54.230
And they are part of the problem
if what they produce actually

00:08:54.230 --> 00:08:58.310
results in these criminalizing
policies, so on and so forth.

00:08:58.310 --> 00:09:02.720
So that became my focus,
laser-sharp, as I moved on.

00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:06.270
But I realized that I can't do
anything about the narrative

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:08.810
problem if I don't address
the structural problem

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:10.430
behind those narratives.

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:11.900
So that's how I came here.

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:15.110
That's why I work on technology
policy, media policy, and all

00:09:15.110 --> 00:09:16.550
of that.

00:09:16.550 --> 00:09:17.990
I'm not a lawyer.

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:19.370
I'm not a policy wonk.

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:20.330
I'm not a technologist.

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:24.780
I'm an organizer who cares
about how meaning is produced

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:26.924
and what that means for
black and brown people

00:09:26.924 --> 00:09:27.590
in this country.

00:09:27.590 --> 00:09:27.856
WILSON WHITE: Very good.

00:09:27.856 --> 00:09:29.990
So I want to stick
with that theme.

00:09:29.990 --> 00:09:32.540
So in preparing for
this talk, I had

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:36.735
this wide-ranging discussion
that I was prepared to do.

00:09:36.735 --> 00:09:40.190
And then on Friday, the verdict
came down in the Castile

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:42.320
shooting case out in Minnesota.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:46.310
And I felt like having
this conversation with you,

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:49.310
I'd be remiss if we didn't
talk about that case,

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:51.080
particularly as
it relates to what

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:54.910
you do in terms of the media
and narratives that come out

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:55.950
of the media.

00:09:55.950 --> 00:09:58.713
So, of course, I was hurt by--

00:09:58.713 --> 00:10:04.310
I still am-- the verdict
itself, a verdict of acquittal.

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:06.190
Not because of that
individual case,

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:10.670
but because it's the next
chapter of essentially

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:16.150
a law-abiding citizen being
killed by a police [INAUDIBLE]..

00:10:16.150 --> 00:10:18.140
This was the next
chapter of that.

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:22.450
But what I was most struck by
was the media response, or lack

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:25.890
of response, to that verdict.

00:10:25.890 --> 00:10:29.470
Is the media just exhausted
with these killers?

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:31.222
Is society exhausted?

00:10:31.222 --> 00:10:32.810
Why is that?

00:10:32.810 --> 00:10:36.560
MALKIA CYRIL: Look, we're
dealing with 400 years

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:39.270
of anti-black criminalization.

00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:42.950
So that is going
to show up in how

00:10:42.950 --> 00:10:46.310
news talks about the murder--

00:10:46.310 --> 00:10:48.520
and I will continue
to call it a murder--

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:52.100
of a black man on Facebook Live.

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:54.500
Everybody could see it.

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:55.300
So let me back up.

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:58.100
So number one, I
always say that you

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:02.860
can't extract 400 years of white
supremacy from any institution

00:11:02.860 --> 00:11:10.180
simply by adding technology.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:12.931
So people thought that by the
fact that you could watch--

00:11:12.931 --> 00:11:14.430
WILSON WHITE: Yeah,
cellphone video.

00:11:14.430 --> 00:11:17.666
MALKIA CYRIL: --the cellphone
videos, Facebook Live,

00:11:17.666 --> 00:11:18.970
body-worn cameras.

00:11:18.970 --> 00:11:20.990
The fact that you could
watch would somehow

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:23.230
increase the measure of justice.

00:11:23.230 --> 00:11:24.430
That's not the case.

00:11:24.430 --> 00:11:26.240
Watching is not justice.

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:28.240
It's just watching.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:30.310
So I'll say this.

00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:33.040
Number one, I'm hurt.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:37.420
But I also understand that
this is a structural problem.

00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:43.030
These news outlets are at
the very top, mostly white.

00:11:43.030 --> 00:11:45.900
At the very top,
they're mostly men.

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:47.830
That is just the fact.

00:11:47.830 --> 00:11:49.240
And so when it
comes time to make

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:52.200
editorial decisions,
about, number one,

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:58.750
do you take the official
word of police as the truth?

00:11:58.750 --> 00:12:02.290
That's the first question
that often these journalists

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:05.380
have to answer when they're
reporting on these cases.

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:07.900
So, for example, the
sister who was just

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:10.450
murdered yesterday in Seattle--

00:12:10.450 --> 00:12:15.090
a pregnant black woman
called the police

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:17.470
to report a burglary,
opened the door.

00:12:17.470 --> 00:12:19.840
She had a knife, presumptively--

00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:22.520
presumably, rather, because
she was being burgled.

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:24.220
She thought she
was being burgled.

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:25.480
She had mental health issues.

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:27.770
They shot her almost on-site.

00:12:27.770 --> 00:12:29.950
She's dead in front
of her three children.

00:12:29.950 --> 00:12:30.116
WILSON WHITE: Yeah.

00:12:30.116 --> 00:12:31.115
And she called the cops.

00:12:31.115 --> 00:12:33.990
MALKIA CYRIL: She called them.

00:12:33.990 --> 00:12:38.615
And whether we're talking
about black men, black women,

00:12:38.615 --> 00:12:41.530
our Muslim brothers and
sisters across race who are

00:12:41.530 --> 00:12:44.270
being murdered by vigilantes.

00:12:44.270 --> 00:12:47.730
Because I want to really
also say that police--

00:12:47.730 --> 00:12:49.470
it's not just the
official police.

00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:51.070
It's also those who
feel that they've

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:56.260
been deputized by this
heightened white supremacy

00:12:56.260 --> 00:12:58.120
that we're dealing
with right now.

00:12:58.120 --> 00:13:00.110
