00:38:38.810 --> 00:38:41.140
by media ignoring
or misrepresenting

00:38:41.140 --> 00:38:42.136
their narratives?

00:38:42.136 --> 00:38:44.510
I think of the way Native
Americans and African Americans

00:38:44.510 --> 00:38:47.630
have been portrayed over time,
and how net neutrality can open

00:38:47.630 --> 00:38:50.752
pathways for community media.

00:38:50.752 --> 00:38:53.210
MALKIA CYRIL: Let me take the
second part of that question.

00:38:53.210 --> 00:38:55.100
Absolutely, net
neutrality can open

00:38:55.100 --> 00:38:57.750
pathways for community
media and community voices,

00:38:57.750 --> 00:38:59.480
allowing a little--

00:38:59.480 --> 00:39:01.010
small dogs to be heard.

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:05.027
The big dogs don't get to
take up all the airtime.

00:39:05.027 --> 00:39:07.710
That said, I think the
fight for reparations

00:39:07.710 --> 00:39:10.250
is a different fight.

00:39:10.250 --> 00:39:11.615
I think it's a necessary fight.

00:39:11.615 --> 00:39:14.451
I think people don't understand
what reparations means.

00:39:14.451 --> 00:39:15.950
A lot of times, you
say reparations,

00:39:15.950 --> 00:39:19.230
people think, oh,
I want my money.

00:39:19.230 --> 00:39:20.600
Let me get my money.

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:24.080
And the thing is
it's not about that.

00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:25.690
It's about shifting power.

00:39:25.690 --> 00:39:27.230
Because one of
the reasons that--

00:39:27.230 --> 00:39:31.160
when slavery was
proclaimed over and there

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:34.320
was a whole period
in American history

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:36.610
called the
reconstruction, right?

00:39:36.610 --> 00:39:39.410
And where there were all those
promises made to black people

00:39:39.410 --> 00:39:42.280
about what we were going to
get for our hundreds of years

00:39:42.280 --> 00:39:42.980
of enslavement.

00:39:42.980 --> 00:39:46.610
And none of those
things came to pass.

00:39:46.610 --> 00:39:49.000
A handful of people
got their 40 acres.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:50.690
Most people did not.

00:39:50.690 --> 00:39:52.370
And the reason
that that matters.

00:39:52.370 --> 00:39:57.011
Like today-- I don't you if you
know, but today is Juneteenth.

00:39:57.011 --> 00:39:57.510
Juneteenth!

00:39:57.510 --> 00:39:58.870
[APPLAUSE]

00:39:58.870 --> 00:40:02.760
And why that's important is
all around the country today,

00:40:02.760 --> 00:40:07.940
black people are doing an
action called 40 Acres, 40 Days,

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:11.080
and taking back land all
over this country today.

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:14.040
And why that
matters, I think, is

00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:17.290
because when we take
back physical land,

00:40:17.290 --> 00:40:19.990
there's a correlation
to the digital space we

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:21.330
have to reclaim as well.

00:40:21.330 --> 00:40:23.640
And that's part of how
I see the relationship

00:40:23.640 --> 00:40:25.535
between this fight
around net neutrality

00:40:25.535 --> 00:40:27.540
to this fight around land.

00:40:27.540 --> 00:40:29.580
We have to actually--

00:40:29.580 --> 00:40:30.750
land matters, right?

00:40:30.750 --> 00:40:35.940
Native Americans understand
that because their people were--

00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:38.770
genocide against our
indigenous brothers and sisters

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:40.290
was for the land
and for what was

00:40:40.290 --> 00:40:43.480
inside of the land or water--
the natural resources.

00:40:43.480 --> 00:40:45.810
Folks didn't just steal
Africans from Africa.

00:40:45.810 --> 00:40:49.995
They also stole gold, ivory, and
all kinds of other resources.

00:40:49.995 --> 00:40:55.830
So when we understand how
Europe and America came

00:40:55.830 --> 00:40:58.380
to have the level of
wealth that they do.

00:40:58.380 --> 00:41:00.720
And we understand
that that wealth

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:05.780
is built on stolen property,
on the theft, on laws broken,

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:08.330
on lives and bodies broken,
then we can actually

00:41:08.330 --> 00:41:12.330
understand reparations in
a completely different way.

00:41:12.330 --> 00:41:15.070
You don't need to give me
something that I haven't heard.

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:16.500
It ain't about that.

00:41:16.500 --> 00:41:18.364
You stole from the people.

00:41:18.364 --> 00:41:19.780
You stole from the
people in order

00:41:19.780 --> 00:41:21.420
to create your own wealth.

00:41:21.420 --> 00:41:24.540
And that wealth now needs
to belong back to the people

00:41:24.540 --> 00:41:25.940
that you stole it from.

00:41:25.940 --> 00:41:27.870
And so that's the
same idea when we

00:41:27.870 --> 00:41:31.110
think about digital equality.

00:41:31.110 --> 00:41:34.470
We're also talking about
claiming digital space,

00:41:34.470 --> 00:41:38.430
claiming that space, giving it
to those whose content actually

00:41:38.430 --> 00:41:39.787
is your bank.

00:41:39.787 --> 00:41:41.370
That's where you're
getting your money

00:41:41.370 --> 00:41:46.180
from is all the people
that's actually online.

00:41:46.180 --> 00:41:49.536
SPEAKER 1: Question
in the back here.

00:41:49.536 --> 00:41:52.560
WILSON WHITE: I'll
repeat the question.

00:41:52.560 --> 00:41:55.269
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:55.269 --> 00:41:56.685
WILSON WHITE: So
tell me what this

00:41:56.685 --> 00:42:00.570
has fared-- but essentially, can
we attack some of this problem

00:42:00.570 --> 00:42:03.050
through the educational
system at the earliest ages,

00:42:03.050 --> 00:42:07.710
getting young people to see
the world in a broader context

00:42:07.710 --> 00:42:11.810
and not using educational
system to deconstruct

00:42:11.810 --> 00:42:13.470
some of these
preconceived biases that

00:42:13.470 --> 00:42:16.725
are baked into society?

00:42:16.725 --> 00:42:18.100
MALKIA CYRIL: So
they did a study

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:21.170
and they found that
by the age of five,

00:42:21.170 --> 00:42:25.890
children already very
serious racial biases.

00:42:25.890 --> 00:42:28.130
And that's before
you've gone to school.

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:33.050
So I just want to say that
to start out with, right?

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:35.280
I think it's
important-- a couple

00:42:35.280 --> 00:42:36.630
of things that are important.

00:42:36.630 --> 00:42:40.450
One is my sister actually
runs a daycare center.

00:42:40.450 --> 00:42:43.780
And it's a daycare center
focused on black children.

00:42:43.780 --> 00:42:45.770
It's an Afrocentric
daycare center.

00:42:45.770 --> 00:42:49.000
And they drum in the morning
with their little djembes,

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.710
and they have a
cute, little time.

00:42:51.710 --> 00:42:54.450
But one of the reasons that I
think is so important that she

00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:57.210
has this daycare center--
it's called Little Maroons--

00:42:57.210 --> 00:43:01.425
is because, actually, we
have to teach each other how

00:43:01.425 --> 00:43:02.790
to be free.

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:04.860
And I think that
freedom is something

00:43:04.860 --> 00:43:08.390
that I think black people
in the fight for freedom,

00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:12.150
this constant quest for
freedom, is something

00:43:12.150 --> 00:43:16.510
that black people have
generously and brilliantly

00:43:16.510 --> 00:43:19.060
offered to the rest of society.

00:43:19.060 --> 00:43:20.980
Because actually,
the fight for freedom

00:43:20.980 --> 00:43:23.160
is not only a fight
for black folk.

00:43:23.160 --> 00:43:25.590
It's also a fight for everyone
else, including white folk.

00:43:25.590 --> 00:43:29.390
The white folks are
imprisoned by white supremacy

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:32.920
the same way the jailer
is imprisoned by the jail.

00:43:32.920 --> 00:43:36.650
So what I want to say is this.

00:43:36.650 --> 00:43:40.255
Yes, the educational system
is part of the infrastructures

00:43:40.255 --> 00:43:42.210
that produce meaning.

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:45.350
When we think about media,
we think about technology,

00:43:45.350 --> 00:43:48.320
we also should be thinking
about the educational system

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:51.660
as part of that setup, right?

00:43:51.660 --> 00:43:54.560
But the goal should not
be to teach children not

00:43:54.560 --> 00:43:57.330
to see each other,
but to see people

00:43:57.330 --> 00:44:01.520
as not black or not white.

00:44:01.520 --> 00:44:02.460
I am black.

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:05.130
I would like to be seen as such.

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:08.850
And with my blackness comes
a history and a positioning

00:44:08.850 --> 00:44:10.700
in society and a struggle.

00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:13.890
And it's very rich and I
think it has a lot to offer.

00:44:13.890 --> 00:44:16.380
So I don't believe that
we should be teaching

00:44:16.380 --> 00:44:18.650
our children to be colorblind.

00:44:18.650 --> 00:44:20.470
I think that that
is actually false.

00:44:20.470 --> 00:44:22.540
I think we should be
teaching our children

00:44:22.540 --> 00:44:23.820
to be freedom fighters.

00:44:23.820 --> 00:44:27.340
And we should be teaching
them how to survive.

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:31.484
Throughout history, if
you live by the river,

00:44:31.484 --> 00:44:33.650
you teach your child where
to go in the river, where

00:44:33.650 --> 00:44:34.670
not to go in the river.

00:44:34.670 --> 00:44:38.140
You teach your children
how to survive around fire.

00:44:38.140 --> 00:44:40.695
You teach them how to
live in the context

00:44:40.695 --> 00:44:44.430
and natural environment
that is around them.

00:44:44.430 --> 00:44:45.900
We also have to
teach our children

00:44:45.900 --> 00:44:48.900
how to live in the political
environment that is around

00:44:48.900 --> 00:44:49.500
them.

00:44:49.500 --> 00:44:51.030
And so that means--

00:44:51.030 --> 00:44:53.942
we used to have home
economics classes.

00:44:53.942 --> 00:44:56.150
But you know, when are we
going to teach our children

00:44:56.150 --> 00:44:59.220
how to balance
checkbooks and how

00:44:59.220 --> 00:45:02.400
to protect themselves online?

00:45:02.400 --> 00:45:04.980
All of this is
part of being free

00:45:04.980 --> 00:45:08.070
in the political
environment that we are in.

00:45:08.070 --> 00:45:10.300
So number one, let's
teach our children

00:45:10.300 --> 00:45:11.390
to be freedom fighters.

00:45:11.390 --> 00:45:14.140
Number two, let's not teach
them to be colorblind.

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:16.870
Number three, yes, let's
use the educational system,

00:45:16.870 --> 00:45:19.180
but understand that all those
same biases are baked in.

00:45:19.180 --> 00:45:21.830
So if you want to use
the educational system,

00:45:21.830 --> 00:45:24.875
we actually need to
organize around that.

00:45:24.875 --> 00:45:26.250
We need to change
the curriculum.

00:45:26.250 --> 00:45:28.900
We need to change how
teachers are trained.

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:32.970
It's not just about teaching
kids to be nice to each other.

00:45:32.970 --> 00:45:33.950
You feel me?

00:45:33.950 --> 00:45:38.230
We need to actually
train them to organize.

00:45:38.230 --> 00:45:41.110
All over the world people know
who the president of the United

00:45:41.110 --> 00:45:42.442
States is.

00:45:42.442 --> 00:45:47.600
Do you know who the
president of Mozambique is?

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:49.935
I'm just saying,
we dumb up in here.

00:45:49.935 --> 00:45:51.217
You know what I'm saying?

00:45:51.217 --> 00:45:52.550
I'm telling you, you might know.

00:45:52.550 --> 00:45:53.712
Did you raise your hand?

00:45:53.712 --> 00:45:54.188
AUDIENCE: I'm actually
asking a question.

00:45:54.188 --> 00:45:55.140
MALKIA CYRIL: Oh, you're
asking a question?

00:45:55.140 --> 00:45:56.092
I don't know either.

00:45:56.092 --> 00:45:57.520
I'm dumb, too.

00:45:57.520 --> 00:46:00.476
I'm saying we have a
terrible educational system.

00:46:00.476 --> 00:46:01.540
You know what I'm saying?

00:46:01.540 --> 00:46:04.340
We got little children in
Palestine running around,

00:46:04.340 --> 00:46:07.340
know exactly what's going
on up in United States.

00:46:07.340 --> 00:46:09.350
Feel me, we do
not know the same.

00:46:09.350 --> 00:46:11.260
Adults do not know the same.

00:46:11.260 --> 00:46:14.520
So there is an entire
overhaul that we

00:46:14.520 --> 00:46:16.200
need in our education system.

00:46:16.200 --> 00:46:19.550
And I can tell you,
Betsy DeVos is not

00:46:19.550 --> 00:46:21.162
going to bring that to you.

00:46:21.162 --> 00:46:22.620
She's not going to
do that for you.

00:46:22.620 --> 00:46:24.536
WILSON WHITE: I'm not
going to touch that one.

00:46:24.536 --> 00:46:27.325
MALKIA CYRIL: I'm just going
to be the one to say it myself.

00:46:27.325 --> 00:46:27.950
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:29.900
So first, thanks for coming.

00:46:29.900 --> 00:46:32.661
This is a great conversation.

00:46:32.661 --> 00:46:34.160
I want to just get
back to something

00:46:34.160 --> 00:46:35.720
that you mentioned earlier.

00:46:35.720 --> 00:46:39.710
You talked about basically,
like the criminalization

00:46:39.710 --> 00:46:42.410
of black as itself, right?

00:46:42.410 --> 00:46:46.570
And how that gets
perpetuated in the media

00:46:46.570 --> 00:46:48.760
as the media being
part of the problem.

00:46:48.760 --> 00:46:51.095
One thing I'm
curious about is as--

00:46:51.095 --> 00:46:52.910
Father's Day was just
yesterday, right?

00:46:57.020 --> 00:47:01.080
The narrative has been for years
that black fathers are absent,

00:47:01.080 --> 00:47:01.940
right?

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:06.160
And then, a couple years ago,
they do an actual study on it.

00:47:06.160 --> 00:47:09.680
And they find that black
fathers are the most involved

00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:11.900
in their children's lives.

00:47:11.900 --> 00:47:14.390
Yet, that narrative
is not the narrative

00:47:14.390 --> 00:47:17.070
that's going to still be talked
about day in and day out.

00:47:17.070 --> 00:47:19.250
So when people talk
about black parents,

00:47:19.250 --> 00:47:21.550
they're still thinking
that they're absent.

00:47:21.550 --> 00:47:24.560
I'm curious about
your thoughts on--

00:47:24.560 --> 00:47:27.575
how do we spread
these narratives

00:47:27.575 --> 00:47:30.780
and make those the
new stereotypes

00:47:30.780 --> 00:47:35.970
that we give to black folks as
opposed to the negative ones?

00:47:35.970 --> 00:47:41.030
MALKIA CYRIL:
Transforming narratives

00:47:41.030 --> 00:47:45.500
is a long-haul project.

00:47:45.500 --> 00:47:49.430
People think that we can
insert some new talking

00:47:49.430 --> 00:47:52.300
points, messages, and there's
going to be a new story.

00:47:52.300 --> 00:47:55.900
But these narratives
aren't about what's said.

00:47:55.900 --> 00:48:00.110
These narratives are
produced by how things are.

00:48:00.110 --> 00:48:02.960
Do you understand
what I'm saying?

00:48:02.960 --> 00:48:05.750
Communications
experts always are

00:48:05.750 --> 00:48:10.160
very interested in neuroscience
and how people think,

00:48:10.160 --> 00:48:13.640
and how to make brain maps
and understand information.

00:48:13.640 --> 00:48:16.670
And one of the
things that is clear

00:48:16.670 --> 00:48:19.600
is that simply
telling people facts

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:21.640
doesn't change
what they believe.

00:48:21.640 --> 00:48:23.206
You know what I mean?

00:48:23.206 --> 00:48:24.652
They'd be like, you lying.

00:48:24.652 --> 00:48:25.579
They'd be just like--

00:48:25.579 --> 00:48:26.370
WILSON WHITE: Fake.

00:48:26.370 --> 00:48:26.794
MALKIA CYRIL: Yeah.

00:48:26.794 --> 00:48:27.642
That's fake.

00:48:27.642 --> 00:48:29.070
That's not real.

00:48:29.070 --> 00:48:34.190
And that's because everything
else affirms the lie.

00:48:34.190 --> 00:48:38.420
So all the way to the--

00:48:38.420 --> 00:48:41.150
if you over-incarcerate
black people,

00:48:41.150 --> 00:48:43.550
you have one or two
explanations for that,

00:48:43.550 --> 00:48:49.121
either racial discrimination
or black criminality.

00:48:49.121 --> 00:48:49.620
That's it.

00:48:49.620 --> 00:48:52.620
Those are the two explanations
for over-incarceration.

00:48:52.620 --> 00:48:56.180
We can produce facts that
demonstrate racial bias, which

00:48:56.180 --> 00:48:58.180
we have many, many times.

00:48:58.180 --> 00:49:01.610
And yet, you have a huge
portion of the population

00:49:01.610 --> 00:49:04.470
that believes that the
answer is black criminality.

00:49:04.470 --> 00:49:06.580
And you cannot convince
them otherwise.

00:49:06.580 --> 00:49:11.440
So I'm of the mind that while
narrative change is necessary,

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:14.770
I'm of the mind that it will
come about because of material

00:49:14.770 --> 00:49:15.940
change.

00:49:15.940 --> 00:49:18.110
We actually have
to change the laws.

00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:20.870
We actually have to change
the way judges work.

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:25.850
We actually have-- we have to
change the material conditions,

00:49:25.850 --> 00:49:30.596
and those will begin to
affect the narrative.

00:49:30.596 --> 00:49:34.390
Kwame Ture said, it don't
matter if you want to lynch me.

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:36.450
It matters if you have
the power to lynch me.

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:39.120
So you could say or
believe whatever you want.

00:49:39.120 --> 00:49:39.736
That's fine.

00:49:39.736 --> 00:49:41.780
You could think that
black fathers are absent

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:44.300
all day and night if that's
what you want to believe.

00:49:44.300 --> 00:49:50.190
But do you have the power to
then defund black families?

00:49:50.190 --> 00:49:53.120
Because if you do as a
result of that stereotype,

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:56.360
that's where I feel like
we need to make the change.

00:49:56.360 --> 00:50:01.333
I think simply saying new
things, it doesn't work.

00:50:01.333 --> 00:50:05.330
It doesn't work when an entire
system around those words

00:50:05.330 --> 00:50:07.729
tells you something else.

00:50:07.729 --> 00:50:10.145
WILSON WHITE: I think we have
time for two more questions,

00:50:10.145 --> 00:50:14.061
if we have any from
the audience here?

00:50:14.061 --> 00:50:14.560
All right.

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:15.470
Oh, we have one.

00:50:15.470 --> 00:50:18.750
And I have the last one.

00:50:18.750 --> 00:50:22.190
MALKIA CYRIL: When he
said two, he meant one.

00:50:22.190 --> 00:50:24.330
AUDIENCE: Do you
predict a resurgence

00:50:24.330 --> 00:50:26.700
of very aggressive
color discrimination

00:50:26.700 --> 00:50:30.427
and other disenfranchising
ways to affect communities

00:50:30.427 --> 00:50:31.010
in the future?

00:50:31.010 --> 00:50:32.560
So my conflict with
this when I was

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:34.380
hearing about
[INAUDIBLE] election

00:50:34.380 --> 00:50:37.234
and hearing about other
governments and other people

00:50:37.234 --> 00:50:39.400
getting involved in it, it
reminds me really quickly

00:50:39.400 --> 00:50:41.160
of [INAUDIBLE] in Tennessee.

00:50:41.160 --> 00:50:45.252
It reminds me of very
quickly gerrymandering laws

00:50:45.252 --> 00:50:47.710
that we've still struggled to
deal with the last 400 years,

00:50:47.710 --> 00:50:48.105
right?

00:50:48.105 --> 00:50:49.350
So I imagine in the
next few elections

00:50:49.350 --> 00:50:51.624
we're going to see this in a
much more aggressive fashion.

00:50:51.624 --> 00:50:53.332
